member.example:
    Below example uses the member variable "A" as the equality comparer.

    public class MyClass
    {
	    public string A;
    }

    void Main()
    {
	    var x = new MyClass() { A = "One" };
	    var y = new MyClass() { A = "Two" };

	    var listA = new List<MyClass>() { x, y};

	    listA.Contains(y, new SelectorEqualityComparer<MyClass,string>((x1) => x1.A, (x2,y2) => x2 == y2)).Dump();	
    }


    Returns true.

    Below example uses the member variable "A" as the equality comparer.

    public class MyClass
    {
	    public string A;
    }

    void Main()
    {
	    var x = new MyClass() { A = "One" };
	    var y = new MyClass() { A = "Two" };

	    var listA = new List<MyClass>() { x, y};

	    listA.Contains(y, new SelectorStringEqualityComparer<MyClass>((x1) => x1.A).Dump();	
    }


    Returns true.

    Below example uses the member variable "A" as the equality comparer.

    public class MyClass
    {
	    public string A;
    }

    void Main()
    {
	    var x = new MyClass() { A = "One" };
	    var y = new MyClass() { A = "Two" };

	    var listA = new List<MyClass>() { y, x }; //Reverse X and Y so that we can actually perform a sort!

	    listA.Sort(new SelectorComparer<MyClass,string>((x1) => x1.A, (x2,y2) => x2.CompareTo(y2))).Dump();	
    }


    Returns {{A="One"}, {A="Two"}}.

